<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence to: _x000b_The ‘Energy and Climate Change’ Select Committee's inquiry on ‘Carbon Capture and Storage’</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Resus Technology Ltd (HOTCCS09)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">xecutive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> summary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is reasonable to presume that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> baring the catastrophic collapse of modern society</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the ongoing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and every growing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">need for energy, specifically electricity, will necessitate the continued use of carbon fuels for some considerable time to come </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">refore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> some means decarbonising the electricity supply, both in the UK and world wide, will be needed. Furthermore any substantial move towards renewable sources of energy for electricity supply will require systems to mitigate supply intermittency </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">including long term (seasonal) variations and currently the only viable systems for doing this at the scale </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be needed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> probably</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> back</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">up </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">generation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">using fossil fuels, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">possibly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nuclear</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> power</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, although nuclear’s slow response would make unsui</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">table in many situations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bearing this in mind there is an emerging technology that not only has the potential to substantially reduce the cost of CCS, both by reducing capture costs and substantially increasing power generation efficiency</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This technolog</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could also provide a solution </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> energy storage and backup generation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to support power generation from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> intermittent renewables (e.g. wind, wave and solar) if</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> instead of CCS we implement a Power Generation Infrastructure (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PGI</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) based on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CCR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Carbon Captu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re &amp; Recycling). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The core technology that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enable the implementation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of such a system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Direct Carbon Fuel Cell), which also has the potential to provide a mechanism for decarbonising the shipping industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I came across DCFC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">technology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a few years ago whilst generally researching renewable energy and clean power generation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, including CCS,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and immediately realised that this was a technology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that could make a seismic change to the cost of implementing CCS comp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ared to the current pre and post combustion technologies. </span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The DCFC works by the same principle as hydrogen fuel cells</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(HFC), i.e. it converts carbon (fuels</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, e.g. coal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, bio-char etc.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) directly into electrical power electrochemically, but has two particular</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> advantages</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-15.3pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">First</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it has about a 20% higher efficiency (about 80% achievable double that of thermal coal) and second carbon (or carbon fuels) are much easier to store than hydrogen. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-15.3pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The waste product fro a DCFC is a stream pure CO2 so no additional capt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ure technology is required, although </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">compression and storage are still required. </span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> technology is not too dissimilar from some of the currently available</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> commercial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> high temperature </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">HFCs that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> employ solid oxide and/or molten carbonate electrolytes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> so even though this technology is not proven at commercial scale there is no inherent reason to dou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bt that it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> not be.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">From my continued research into renewable power generation it also became clear that quite apart from the massive advantage DCFC tec</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hnology could have over current CCS technologies, particularly when used with thermal coal generation (a fact that apparently has not gone unnoticed by the Chinese</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who have a number of universities working in parallel on this technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">there are a numbe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r of other areas where the DCFC has the potential to provide substantial benefit, three of these are:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-15.3pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Provide a mechanism for massive energy storage combined with on demand power generation which can support renewable power generation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-15.3pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Provide a more effic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ient power train for large scale transport (e.g. shipping) that could include carbon capture to reduce, possibly eliminate, carbon emissions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; text-indent:-15.3pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Provide a much cleaner and much more efficient waste to energy conversion from non-recyclable waste plastic compar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed to incineration.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.65pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In short the DCFC is a disruptive technology for clean power generation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> form carbon, or carbon based, fuels.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Technology</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Description of DCFC operation.</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The DCFC converts the energy in carbon, or carbon rich fuels, directly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">into electricity electrochemically in the same way as the more familiar hydrogen fuel cells do and operate in the region of 700degC, similar to some HFCs that operate at similar temperatures and can run on natural gas by directly reforming the methane to h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ydrogen and CO2. The cell construction is also similar being of the molten carbonate or solid oxide type.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The main differences are that:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-22.53pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The waste product for DCFCs is pure carbon dioxide (CO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) as compared to water (H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">O) for HFCs. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-23.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The fuel for DCFCs is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">normally solid carbon, this is presents one of the major challenges of DCFCs, namely transporting the fuel to the electrode reaction zone.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-22.53pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The maximum theoretical efficiency of a DCFC is 100% compared to 83% for a HFC, maximum practical efficiencies are ab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">out 80% and 60% respectively. </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Because of the high temperature that a DCFC operates at it would be possible to operate them in a combine cycle system, using waste heat to power a steam turbine/Rankine cycle raising the overall system efficiency even </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">further.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">State of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> technology:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is currently being developed in a number of countries, including the UK and China. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To my knowledge there are no commercially viable devices at this time, Prof John Irvine at St. Andrews University (UK) is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">currently developing/researching 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> generation small scale cells. Prof. Irvine is to my knowledge the leading UK authority on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DCFCs and could provide a clearer picture of the state of current DCFC development.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Advantages of DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for CCS</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DCFC </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-22.53pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Reduced cost!</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CO2 capture i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> an integral part of the process so no additional CO2 capture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> equipment is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">required</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> just compression and storage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (or recycling/reuse CCR)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-23.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Greatly Improved efficiency!</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The practical efficiency of the process using carbon/coal fo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r fuel is approximately 80%, about double that of unabated coa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l and about two and a half times better than coal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> CCS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. One of the consequences of this is that for a given sized power plant the fuel usage would be about half that of a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> thermal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">coal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">power </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">station and the fuel bill savings over the life of the plant are likely to be higher than the capital costs. Put another way it would be cost effective to pull</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">down a brand new coal power station and replace it with DCFC technology, especially if the coal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">power station had CCS.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-22.53pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Easy and cheap energy storage!</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Use of a solid fuel, coal, bio-char, synthetic carbon (see below) provides an easy and cheap energy storage mechanism that enables energy stockpiling </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improving energy security,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as was highlighted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">breaking </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of the miners strike in 1984 because power stations had about 6 months of coal reserves.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-23.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On demand power generation!</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DCFCs, in common with fuel cells in general, have a fast output response which would allow them to be used for both base load and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> peaking power generation.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-22.53pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If we don’t develop DCFC and the Chinese do!</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By way of comparison between the current post combustion CCS and CCS based on DCFC technology, if DCFC approach was likened to DVD technology then post combustion CCS would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at best </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">equivalent to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">video tape technology. If DCFC technology becomes commercially viable, which I believe is highly likely (the Chinese have 5 universities working in parallel on it) then I doubt whether there will be a market for bolt-on CCS technology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for exi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sting coal powerstations!</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> an enabling </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">technology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> support int</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ermittent renewable generation.</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As stated earlier</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> intermittent renewable generation requires backup generation in some form but that backup needs to cope with a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wide range </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f intermittency</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> scenarios</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">from short term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of the order of minutes to hours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">through medium</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">term (days) to long term (weeks, seasonal).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Short term variability could probably be provide by current technologies, particularly pumped hydro storage but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> if the UK is to rely on a substantial proportion of generation coming from wind, wave </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> solar then</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> medium and long term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">intermittency could require storage of  several TWh (1,000’sof GWhs) of energy storage if backup generation from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">finite </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fossil </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">energy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sources is to be avoided.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DCFC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">technology has the potential to provide a mechanism that could support cost effective solution to this scale of storage. Using carbon as an energy storage vector </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provides a cheap</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, easy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, massive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">long term, energy storage mechanism. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If coupled with temporary CO2 storage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> then</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cheap or surplus intermittent renewable energy resources could be used to regenerate the carbon</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, or carbonaceous</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> fuel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from the CO2 when available. This</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> mechanism</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is effectivel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y a synthetic version of photosynthesis but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ould be about ten times more efficient and would not require additional nutrients</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/fertiliser to operate resulting is a pure carbon fuel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> whereas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> biomass contains a number of impurities, such as sulphur compounds, which result in the need for waste gas cleaning.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Furthermore using a synthetic route for CO2 conversion the carbon fuels does not require arable land which could otherwise grow crops.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is process </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could be described as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a Synthetic Closed Carbon Cycle </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">incorporating CCR, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at least carbon neutral and could be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carbon negative.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By way of comparison</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">multi </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">TWh </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hydrogen </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">storage scheme has been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">considered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which involves creating massive un</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">der </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ground</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> chambers to store high pressure hydrogen and these have to be hydrogen gas tight</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, quite a challenge</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> If the hydrogen was stored at 700 Bar 1 TWh would need about 400,000m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of storage space. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By comparison 1TWh of carbon </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could be stored in a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">100,0</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">00</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hole</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> about the size of  a football pitch and about 20m deep with a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> simple</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> plastic cover to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">protect the carbon from the elements</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and could be sited almost anywhere.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Another comparison</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with pumped hydro storage. The Dinorwig facility in N. Wales stores less than 10GWh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of energy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, less than 15minutes of average UK electricity usage. If the upper reservoir for Dinorwig was filled with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">carbon which powered DCFC generating technology then it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would store more than 3 months of average UK electricity usage.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CCR is likely to be far more socially acceptable than CCS; there is currently a large amount of opposition to the idea of permanently storing humongous quantities of CO2 underground. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re many other advantages of using Synthetic Closed Carbon Cycle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, if you would like a more detailed presentation of its potential please contact the author.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The DCFC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for decarbonising shipping</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Most modern ships use diesel (bunker fuel) generator sets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with electric motor propulsion. The diesel engines can approach 50% electrical efficiency and operate in combined heat and power mode, the 50% waste heat is used provide space heating, hot water and desalination functions.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Using a DCFC for power generation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would increase the electrical efficiency and heating and hot water functions could be implemented more efficiently using heat pumps, a COP of about 4 should be achievable giving about 75% reduction in energy needed for heating functions.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The simplicity of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> CO2 capture with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DCFCs should make it viable to add this to the ships power train without a massive cost penalty.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The DCFC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for energy from waste</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A large proportion of waste currently going to landfill is un-recyclable plastics, and plastics have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a high</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">energy content, some have HHV’s (calorific values) equivalent to petrol and deisel.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The DCFC can use plastics directly as a feedstock/fuel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> resulting in a much higher </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">conversion efficiency than can be achieved with conventional waste to energy using inciner</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ation, probably about three times higher. Therefore separation and storage of all waste plastic should be considered whilst DCFC technology is being developed.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Investment in DCFC R&amp;D</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The DCFC has the potential to be a disruptive and game changing technology, not just with regard to CCS but also as an enabling technology for renewable energy and quite possibly a route to decarbonising shipping. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I would therefore recommend that funding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for this area of research and development should at least be given the same level of priority as current CCS technologies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CCS needs to be considered in conjunction with power generation as a whole system which in turn also take into account other environm</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ental aspects such as waste management. We will not get the best solutions for clean power generation if CCS is considered in isolation</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCFC Expert advisors:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I would recommend contacting the following </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">two people to gain further insights into the benefits/</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">potential and current state of development of DCFCs </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 90pt; text-indent:-41.63pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Prof John Irvine, St Andrews University, UK</span><br /><a href="mailto:JTSI@St-Andrews.ac.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">JTSI@St-Andrews.ac.uk</span></a></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 90pt; text-indent:-42.3pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">John F. Cooper</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">John F. Cooper Consulting, LLC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (US)</span><br /><a href="mailto:JFCconsult@Comcast.net"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">JFCconsult@Comcast.net</span></a></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>